WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.810 --> 00:00:02.170
- It happens to me all the time

00:00:02.170 --> 00:00:04.170
and it happened just this week.

00:00:04.170 --> 00:00:07.430
A young person I'd never
met introduced himself to me

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:10.270
and said that when he saw our guest today,

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:12.260
on an earlier episode of this program,

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:16.243
he felt he was seeing a
man who knew how to think.

00:00:16.243 --> 00:00:20.028
Dr. Thomas Sowell on
Uncommon Knowledge now.

00:00:20.028 --> 00:00:22.861
(classical music)

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:31.910
Welcome to Uncommon Knowledge.

00:00:31.910 --> 00:00:33.650
I'm Peter Robinson.

00:00:33.650 --> 00:00:36.180
Thomas Sowell has studied
and taught economics,

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:39.160
intellectual history, and
social policy in institutions

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:42.883
that include Cornell,
Brandeis, UCLA, and Amherst.

00:00:42.883 --> 00:00:45.160
Now a senior fellow at
the Hoover Institution

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:47.915
Dr. Sowell has published
more than a dozen books,

00:00:47.915 --> 00:00:51.230
including the classic
a conflict of visions.

00:00:51.230 --> 00:00:54.900
Coming soon, a revised edition
of his most recent volume,

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:57.067
Discrimination and Disparities.

00:00:57.067 --> 00:00:58.840
Tom Sowell, welcome.

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:00.026
- Thank you.

00:01:00.026 --> 00:01:03.990
- You grew up in Harlem,
dropped out of high school

00:01:03.990 --> 00:01:07.190
to join the Marine Corps
during the Korean War,

00:01:07.190 --> 00:01:09.702
received an undergraduate
degree from Harvard,

00:01:09.702 --> 00:01:11.856
a masters from Columbia,

00:01:11.856 --> 00:01:15.228
and your doctorate from
the University of Chicago.

00:01:15.228 --> 00:01:18.530
All of which pales by
comparison with the fact

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:20.909
that you once tried out
for the Brooklyn Dodgers.

00:01:20.909 --> 00:01:22.860
(laughing)

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:25.550
But during this period from Harlem

00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:28.210
to the University of Chicago,

00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:30.150
throughout your 20s you've said,

00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:33.670
you spent most of the decade
of your 20s as a Marxist.

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:35.060
- Yes.

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:35.893
- Why?

00:01:35.893 --> 00:01:36.730
What was it...

00:01:37.954 --> 00:01:39.800
what was the attraction?

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:42.398
- Well I guess I first was...

00:01:42.398 --> 00:01:44.300
very puzzled.

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:46.670
See there's one little
correction I would make.

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:51.670
At age 16 I was a dropout,
high school dropout,

00:01:51.872 --> 00:01:56.872
and I went to work full time
as a Western Union messenger.

00:02:00.349 --> 00:02:02.120
- Delivering telegrams.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:02.953
- Delivering telegrams.

00:02:02.953 --> 00:02:04.680
- We better say that because
there will be a generation

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.550
that won't know what Western
Union was, but go ahead.

00:02:06.550 --> 00:02:07.700
- Yeah that's true too.

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:12.870
And so I were I worked
in the area of Manhattan

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:14.090
called Chelsea district,

00:02:14.090 --> 00:02:16.920
which is around 23rd Street, ninth Avenue,

00:02:16.920 --> 00:02:19.350
and at the end of the day

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:21.680
I had several ways of getting back home.

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:24.510
The easiest and fastest
way was with a subway,

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:26.890
which was a nickel in those days.

00:02:26.890 --> 00:02:31.618
When I was feeling flushed I
might go for a bus for a dime

00:02:31.618 --> 00:02:34.250
and then when I was
really getting reckless

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:36.790
I would take the fifth Avenue bus,

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:40.760
which was the elite of
the buses for 15 cents.

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:42.500
So I would walk over the fifth avenue,

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:44.981
take that bus, and it would take me up

00:02:44.981 --> 00:02:48.890
through all the glamorous
parts of fifth avenue,

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:50.769
past the Empire State Building,

00:02:50.769 --> 00:02:55.133
past the great stores
and things of that sort.

00:02:55.133 --> 00:02:58.393
And then on 57th Street it would turn

00:02:58.393 --> 00:03:02.020
and this is just a the elite part of town.

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:03.820
- Sure, right there what park starts.

00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:05.577
- Yes and then...

00:03:05.577 --> 00:03:07.370
park starts at 59th.

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:08.203
- Oh, sorry.

00:03:08.203 --> 00:03:10.190
- 57th that would turn over,

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:13.871
again, the same kind of
scene, pass Carnegie Hall.

00:03:13.871 --> 00:03:17.550
Columbus Circle, there was
no Trump Tower at that time,

00:03:17.550 --> 00:03:20.238
and on up to about 72nd Street

00:03:20.238 --> 00:03:24.630
and out to Riverside Drive
which is another elite area.

00:03:24.630 --> 00:03:27.050
So four miles after that
you'd have all these

00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:30.820
wonderful luxury apartment
buildings and so on.

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:34.607
And finally around 129th, 30th street,

00:03:34.607 --> 00:03:38.310
it would go on a long viaduct

00:03:38.310 --> 00:03:40.040
and then he would do a right turn

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.580
back into the occupied area

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:44.393
and there you'd see the tenements.

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:48.120
And I would wonder why is this?

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.913
I mean, why this huge disparity?

00:03:50.913 --> 00:03:53.682
And there was nobody else,

00:03:53.682 --> 00:03:56.830
there was no other other
explanation around.

00:03:56.830 --> 00:03:59.720
There was nothing there
other than Marxism.

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:03.870
I stumbled across, I had not read Marx,

00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:08.870
but I bought a secondhand
pair, set of Encyclopedias.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:13.560
Small set for some ridiculously low price

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.970
and there they met I looked up Karl Marx,

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:18.540
I'd heard the name and
the stuff that he said

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:19.883
seemed to make sense.

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.283
And later on I would get
more and more into it.

00:04:27.553 --> 00:04:31.110
And the argument was that
the rich had gotten rich

00:04:31.110 --> 00:04:33.270
by taking from the poor.

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:35.910
And well that was one explanation,
but what is interesting,

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:38.730
there was no other
explanation out there really.

00:04:38.730 --> 00:04:42.650
And that's true largely in our
colleges/universities today.

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:45.910
- But so by the time you
went to Harvard undergrad,

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:48.913
well so wait, you drop
out at the age of 16,

00:04:48.913 --> 00:04:52.570
and you start reading
Marx in your late teens.

00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:57.550
- I start reading Marx, yes, at age 19.

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:00.050
- Age 19 and then you're
in the Marine Corps

00:05:00.050 --> 00:05:03.428
for a couple years, what
was it, two, three years?

00:05:03.428 --> 00:05:04.261
- Two years.

00:05:04.261 --> 00:05:08.210
It was actually one year,
11 months, and five days,

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:09.501
but who's counting.

00:05:09.501 --> 00:05:10.987
(laughing)

00:05:10.987 --> 00:05:13.830
- So by the time you went to Harvard

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:17.820
you had already become
intellectually engaged with Marxism.

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:18.653
- Yes.

00:05:18.653 --> 00:05:21.450
- And remained, and Harvard
didn't talk you out of it

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:23.730
and the study of economics at Harvard

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:24.900
didn't talk you out of it,

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:26.680
nor did getting a master's at Columbia,

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:30.120
nor did getting a doctorate at Chicago

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:31.820
dissuade you from Marxism.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.450
And you studied with Milton
Friedman of all people,

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:36.617
how could you have sat in
Milton Friedman's classroom

00:05:36.617 --> 00:05:38.300
and remained a Marxist?

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:39.883
- Some people are just stubborn.

00:05:39.883 --> 00:05:41.780
(laughs)

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:44.141
But what really changed me

00:05:44.141 --> 00:05:46.506
was not the University of Chicago,

00:05:46.506 --> 00:05:51.045
it was my first job working
in a professional capacity

00:05:51.045 --> 00:05:52.120
for the government.

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:53.670
I was a summer intern.

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:55.350
- This is after Chicago or?

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:57.020
- No, no, while I was
still a graduate student.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:58.420
- Got it.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:00.300
- And so during the summer vacation

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:03.040
I worked in the US Department of Labor

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:06.891
and I began to realize,
a number of things,

00:06:06.891 --> 00:06:10.640
that the government is not
simply the personification

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:14.200
of the general will
like Rousseau or others.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:15.490
The government is an institution,

00:06:15.490 --> 00:06:17.322
the government institutions

00:06:17.322 --> 00:06:20.220
have their own institutional interests.

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:22.360
One involved in minimum wage law.

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:24.320
I was a big supporter of that,

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:27.210
but I also knew that there was
an argument that minimum wage

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:30.894
laws simply price low
wage workers out of a job

00:06:30.894 --> 00:06:34.557
and my first assignment
dealt with minimum wages

00:06:34.557 --> 00:06:38.210
in Puerto Rico and as I
looked at the numbers,

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:40.410
I would see as they would
jack up the minimum wage,

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:43.680
number of jobs would go down and so forth,

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.290
but there were two explanations.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:46.850
One was that of the economists

00:06:46.850 --> 00:06:49.660
that you priced the people out of a job

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:53.070
and the other was that were hurricanes

00:06:53.070 --> 00:06:55.830
that come through Puerto Rico, you see,

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:59.080
during the sugar harvesting and therefore,

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:00.660
and I was studying the sugar industry,

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:03.080
and therefore it destroyed
a lot of the crop,

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:05.310
therefore you wouldn't
hire as many workers.

00:07:05.310 --> 00:07:06.700
Now in Chicago I'd been taught that

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:08.560
if there are two different theories,

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.860
there should be some empirical
evidence in principle

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:14.840
that could distinguish what
would happen under one theory

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.610
from what would happen under the other.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:19.640
And so I wrestled with that
for the most of the summer

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:22.860
and one morning I came
in and I said, I got it.

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:25.840
We need a data on the amount of sugarcane

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:29.440
standing in the fields
before the hurricane struck

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:31.310
and as I waited for the congratulations

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:34.090
I could see stricken looks
around me in the room,

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:35.513
like this guy has stumbled on something

00:07:35.513 --> 00:07:37.606
that will ruin us all.

00:07:37.606 --> 00:07:40.550
(laughing)

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.380
And they said well, we
don't have those data.

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:44.720
I said, oh, I'll bet the
Department of Agriculture has it.

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:48.071
He said, well, but that
doesn't mean we have it.

00:07:48.071 --> 00:07:51.830
You'd have to have a request
go off the chain of command

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:53.390
to the Secretary of Labor.

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.130
He would then confer it with
the Secretary of Agriculture.

00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:58.030
It would come down the chain of command

00:07:58.030 --> 00:07:59.880
and the Department of Agriculture,

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:01.880
whoever has those numbers and so on.

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:04.830
I said, good, well they say
a journey of a thousand miles

00:08:04.830 --> 00:08:06.380
begins with a single step

00:08:06.380 --> 00:08:09.570
so I will now submit my request
to the Secretary of Labor,

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:10.820
which I did.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:13.959
And I am still patiently
awaiting this reply.

00:08:13.959 --> 00:08:15.383
(laughs)

00:08:15.383 --> 00:08:17.540
- And the institutional
fear of the number was what?

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:19.890
- Oh, the US Department of Labor

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:21.690
administers the minimum wage law

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:26.550
and the money and the
careers of perhaps a third

00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:28.850
or some other significant percentage

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.520
of the Labor Department's other sources

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:33.770
come from administering
the minimum wage law.

00:08:34.727 --> 00:08:36.850
One of the real forces of all this is

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:40.280
that the law itself,
section 4D I still remember,

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:43.590
requires a Labor Department to
study the employment effects

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:47.834
of minimum wages and those
studies are absolutely a farce.

00:08:47.834 --> 00:08:49.962
In fact some years after I left,

00:08:49.962 --> 00:08:54.554
I did an article saying why
those studies were a farce

00:08:54.554 --> 00:08:56.270
and when I came back later on

00:08:56.270 --> 00:08:57.900
to the Labor Department
to do some research,

00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:00.420
one of the older librarians
who remembered me

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:02.710
turn to the younger
librarian and she said,

00:09:02.710 --> 00:09:04.420
this is the man who wrote that article

00:09:04.420 --> 00:09:06.621
that has everybody up in arms.

00:09:06.621 --> 00:09:08.310
(laughs)

00:09:08.310 --> 00:09:13.110
- So you began to be dissuaded of Marxism.

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:14.900
- And of government in general

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:18.420
because the government is not out there

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:21.343
at the personification
of the national interest.

00:09:21.343 --> 00:09:23.100
They have their own interests

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:24.600
and the Labor Department's was clearly

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:27.600
an interest in keeping the minimum wage,

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:31.250
because that's their jobs
and careers and power.

00:09:31.250 --> 00:09:33.720
- In your, which brings us if I may,

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:35.830
to one of my favorite
books, your 2000 book,

00:09:35.830 --> 00:09:37.640
this is a beat-up old copy.

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:40.028
This book A Conflict of Visions.

00:09:40.028 --> 00:09:40.861
- Yes.

00:09:40.861 --> 00:09:43.140
- Which you published in 2007
and you layout, I'm sorry.

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:44.010
- 1987.

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:45.460
- I beg your pardon, 1987?

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.370
- Reprinted in 2007.

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:50.650
- Well beat up is this book,
it turns out this is a reprint.

00:09:50.650 --> 00:09:52.981
Sorry, 1987.

00:09:52.981 --> 00:09:57.350
And you lay out two competing
ways of looking at economics

00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:00.120
and policy, really two competing
ways of looking at life

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:02.450
that go back at least 200 years.

00:10:02.450 --> 00:10:06.111
The constrained vision and
the unconstrained vision.

00:10:06.111 --> 00:10:07.670
The constrained vision,

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:09.360
I'm quoting from A Conflict of Visions

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:13.650
sees the evils of the world
as deriving from the limited

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:17.790
and unhappy choices available
given the inherent moral

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:20.910
and intellectual
limitations of human beings.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:22.290
Close quote.

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:27.279
So the constrained vision
understands itself as constrained

00:10:27.279 --> 00:10:29.858
by the limitations of reality itself.

00:10:29.858 --> 00:10:30.948
- Yes.

00:10:30.948 --> 00:10:31.930
- That's correct?

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:32.763
- Yes.

00:10:33.655 --> 00:10:36.500
In other words, they cannot
proceed as so many do

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:38.480
that good things happen automatically,

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:41.009
but bad things are somebody's fault.

00:10:41.009 --> 00:10:44.290
- Got it, got it, and
then to continue here,

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:45.890
the constrained vision,

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:48.569
again quoting from A Conflict Of Visions,

00:10:48.569 --> 00:10:52.900
for the amelioration improvement
of the human condition,

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:55.160
the constrained vision relies on

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:58.760
certain social processes
such as moral traditions,

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:01.800
the marketplace, or families.

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:03.420
Not government.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:04.403
So explain that.

00:11:05.756 --> 00:11:10.064
Why do we rely on on processes rather than

00:11:10.064 --> 00:11:13.620
the will of the people instituting changes

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:15.794
to improve our condition?

00:11:15.794 --> 00:11:18.636
- Well it doesn't ignore government.

00:11:18.636 --> 00:11:22.570
Even for the market the work
you have to have a government,

00:11:22.570 --> 00:11:26.100
as Europe discovered when
the Roman Empire collapsed

00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:27.943
and the economy has collapsed also.

00:11:30.620 --> 00:11:34.760
But I guess one of the reasons would be

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:37.580
with the government you have
surrogate decision makers

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:39.960
and they cannot possibly know as much

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:42.870
as the individuals
whose personal decisions

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:44.350
have been preempted.

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:46.390
- I see, I see, all right.

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:48.830
Which brings us to the
unconstrained vision.

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:50.953
When again, I'm quoting you,

00:11:50.953 --> 00:11:53.735
when Rousseau said that man is born free

00:11:53.735 --> 00:11:54.568
but everywhere in chains,

00:11:55.992 --> 00:11:58.740
he expressed the essence of
the unconstrained vision,

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:01.210
in which the fundamental
problem is not nature

00:12:01.210 --> 00:12:03.850
or man but institutions.

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:05.590
Would you explain that one?

00:12:05.590 --> 00:12:08.490
- Well he has the notion that, again,

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:10.180
that good things happen naturally

00:12:10.180 --> 00:12:13.270
and if they're bad things it's because

00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:16.220
institutions including civilization itself

00:12:16.220 --> 00:12:18.780
have have made these bad things happen.

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:23.410
And I think that that's
really the implicit assumption

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:26.672
behind a lot of things that
are said on the left today.

00:12:26.672 --> 00:12:30.560
And why in my most recent
book I go to a lot of trouble

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:34.700
to show that in nature there is nothing

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:36.710
resembling equal opportunity.

00:12:36.710 --> 00:12:38.810
That wherever you look around the country,

00:12:39.671 --> 00:12:42.180
around the world, you find people

00:12:42.180 --> 00:12:45.090
who live up in the mountains
poor and backwards,

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:47.351
even in the richest countries.

00:12:47.351 --> 00:12:49.860
Including the United States.

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:52.890
I believe the poorest
country in the United States,

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:57.190
county rather, was in
a mountain community,

00:12:57.190 --> 00:12:59.343
which was almost 100% white.

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:03.920
- Somewhere in Appalachia,
West Virginia, Southern Ohio.

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:08.521
- Yes and men in that
county had a life expectancy

00:13:08.521 --> 00:13:13.521
10 years less than men
in a county in Virginia.

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:20.464
- And the unconstrained
vision says let's fix that.

00:13:20.464 --> 00:13:23.070
Surely we can pass a law
that would improve that

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:25.614
and the constrained vision
says well now wait a moment,

00:13:25.614 --> 00:13:29.990
if people who live in
isolated pockets in mountains

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:33.210
are poor and backwards
all around the world

00:13:33.210 --> 00:13:35.860
and we see this pattern over
and over and over again,

00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:38.750
maybe there's something very
deeply rooted in reality

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:41.920
about that that's hard for us to get at.

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:42.753
Correct?

00:13:42.753 --> 00:13:43.586
- Yes.

00:13:43.586 --> 00:13:44.419
- All right.

00:13:44.419 --> 00:13:47.143
So in the book of A Conflict of Visions,

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:51.760
you're very dispassionate
and very analytical

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:54.420
and you lay out the unconstrained vision

00:13:54.420 --> 00:13:56.790
and you lay out the constrained vision

00:13:56.790 --> 00:14:00.284
and you don't really come out blazing

00:14:00.284 --> 00:14:02.575
in favor of one or the other.

00:14:02.575 --> 00:14:05.630
- That is not a book meant to commit to

00:14:05.630 --> 00:14:09.140
show one vision is better than the other.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:11.380
It's there to show you what what they are

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:15.750
and what you're assuming if you
go one direction or another.

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:17.780
It's to encourage people to understand

00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:20.670
the implicit assumptions behind all this

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:24.210
without which you're just loose ends.

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:25.522
- All right.

00:14:25.522 --> 00:14:29.610
So pondering all this I noticed something,

00:14:29.610 --> 00:14:33.000
a column that you wrote,
this is a couple years ago,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.490
in which you rebutted Nicholas
Kristof of the New York Times

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:39.890
and Kristof had ascribed the gaps

00:14:39.890 --> 00:14:42.680
between African-Americans
and whites in America,

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:44.840
gaps in wealth, gaps in
educational achievement,

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:48.990
the usual gaps and this is
a quotation from Kristof,

00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:51.330
to the lingering effects
of slavery, close quote.

00:14:51.330 --> 00:14:52.681
- Oh yeah.

00:14:52.681 --> 00:14:55.150
- And here's Tom Sowell, quote,

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:59.011
if we wanted to be serious about evidence,

00:14:59.011 --> 00:15:02.250
we might compare where
blacks stood a hundred years

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:04.870
