Even though they may
meet the standards of 80

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:57.120
or 90% of the colleges in America.

00:25:57.120 --> 00:25:59.610
I remember I was first aware of this

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:00.650
when I was teaching at Cornell

00:26:00.650 --> 00:26:03.030
and I found a half the
black students at Cornell

00:26:03.030 --> 00:26:05.360
were on some kind of academic probation.

00:26:05.360 --> 00:26:07.450
And so I went over to the
administration building

00:26:07.450 --> 00:26:09.840
to look up the SATs of these students.

00:26:09.840 --> 00:26:12.270
The average black student
at Cornell at that time

00:26:12.270 --> 00:26:14.343
scored at the 75th percentile.

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:16.610
- Which is pretty darn good.

00:26:16.610 --> 00:26:20.842
- Yes and so that means
that in most colleges

00:26:20.842 --> 00:26:22.340
in this country they would have no trouble

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:24.820
and many of them would
be on the Dean's List.

00:26:24.820 --> 00:26:27.670
But at Cornell, the average
a liberal arts student

00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:30.890
at that time was in the 99th percentile

00:26:30.890 --> 00:26:34.266
and when you're teaching
students like that,

00:26:34.266 --> 00:26:38.763
you teach at a pace that
most people of any race

00:26:38.763 --> 00:26:40.965
cannot keep up with.

00:26:40.965 --> 00:26:43.500
It was always complained
that I was assigning

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:46.100
all kinds of reading but heck,

00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:48.594
I'm teaching kids who are in the top 1%,

00:26:48.594 --> 00:26:52.151
they can keep up with the
reading that I'm assigning.

00:26:52.151 --> 00:26:54.990
- So Cornell was taking
very talented black kids

00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:57.530
and spending four years teaching
them to feel inadequate.

00:26:57.530 --> 00:27:00.033
- Yes and succeeding at that.

00:27:01.561 --> 00:27:03.440
- A couple quotations.

00:27:03.440 --> 00:27:05.610
These are both from the
last affirmative action case

00:27:05.610 --> 00:27:06.800
to reach the Supreme Court,

00:27:06.800 --> 00:27:09.383
last big affirmative action
case to reach the Supreme Court.

00:27:09.383 --> 00:27:12.270
2003 Grutter versus Bollinger.

00:27:12.270 --> 00:27:13.540
Here's the majority opinion,

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:15.700
which was written by
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,

00:27:15.700 --> 00:27:20.670
quote: "The court expects
that 25 years from now

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:24.830
the use of racial preferences
will no longer be necessary."

00:27:24.830 --> 00:27:27.980
This upholding the use of
in a decision, 5-4 decision,

00:27:27.980 --> 00:27:30.230
upholding the use of racial preferences.

00:27:30.230 --> 00:27:31.460
Now, that's quotation one.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:33.660
Here's quotation two, Justice Thomas.

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:36.340
Justice Clarence Thomas in a dissent.

00:27:36.340 --> 00:27:39.627
Quote: "I believe that blacks can achieve

00:27:39.627 --> 00:27:42.217
"in every avenue of American life

00:27:42.217 --> 00:27:45.487
"without the meddling of
university administrators.

00:27:45.487 --> 00:27:47.447
"The Court holds that
racial discrimination

00:27:47.447 --> 00:27:50.617
"and admissions should be
given another 25 years.

00:27:50.617 --> 00:27:53.307
"While I agree that in
25 years these practices

00:27:53.307 --> 00:27:56.589
"will be illegal, they are illegal now."

00:27:56.589 --> 00:27:58.430
(laughing)

00:27:58.430 --> 00:27:59.960
Close quote.

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:03.810
So here's...

00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:05.270
what do you do with the argument

00:28:05.270 --> 00:28:08.610
that Justice O'Connor writing
that majority opinion,

00:28:08.610 --> 00:28:10.590
there's something of the
constrained vision there.

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:13.270
Look we have these, all
universities across the country

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:15.857
are using these racial preferences

00:28:15.857 --> 00:28:18.177
as the basis of admission.

00:28:18.177 --> 00:28:20.810
The best we can hope to do is tell them

00:28:20.810 --> 00:28:22.170
they ought not to be doing it.

00:28:22.170 --> 00:28:24.030
That they should be
developing other standards

00:28:24.030 --> 00:28:26.320
and give them a clock.

00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:27.470
(laughing)

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:29.335
Is that a reasonable thing to do?

00:28:29.335 --> 00:28:32.370
- No, but it's a universal thing to do.

00:28:32.370 --> 00:28:35.154
I wrote a book about affirmative action,

00:28:35.154 --> 00:28:37.930
it was called Affirmative
Action Around The World

00:28:37.930 --> 00:28:40.370
and I made a couple of international trips

00:28:40.370 --> 00:28:42.290
at the expensive of Hoover Institution

00:28:42.290 --> 00:28:44.900
around the world to check
out affirmative action.

00:28:44.900 --> 00:28:47.190
This is one of the most common arguments.

00:28:47.190 --> 00:28:50.260
It is absolutely fallacious
time and time again.

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:53.460
The argument like so much
in the unconstrained vision,

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:57.260
it assumes that we have a
power that we do not have,

00:28:57.260 --> 00:28:59.832
cannot have, and never have had.

00:28:59.832 --> 00:29:02.657
In England there was a man named Scarm

00:29:02.657 --> 00:29:05.700
and it was saying for the
now we must do this in order.

00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:09.744
And in many countries
these programs was set up

00:29:09.744 --> 00:29:12.070
with an actual cutoff date,

00:29:12.070 --> 00:29:15.210
so it was set up in
Malaysia with a cut-off date

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:19.953
I think of around 1990 and in Pakistan

00:29:19.953 --> 00:29:22.610
it was supposed to go for 10 years.

00:29:22.610 --> 00:29:27.610
None of those cut off
dates has meant a thing.

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:30.890
These programs not only
continue, they increase.

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:32.170
They spread.

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:35.328
So the idea that you
can control the future

00:29:35.328 --> 00:29:38.770
because of these wonderful sounding words.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:41.330
I can't think of a country in the world

00:29:41.330 --> 00:29:43.590
where that's ever happened.

00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:45.210
In the case of Pakistan,

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:48.486
they did have an actual cutoff date

00:29:48.486 --> 00:29:51.510
and because people in
the East Pakistan were,

00:29:51.510 --> 00:29:53.610
for whatever historical reason,

00:29:53.610 --> 00:29:55.910
way behind the people in West Pakistan,

00:29:55.910 --> 00:29:59.350
and so there's these preferences
with East Pakistanis.

00:29:59.350 --> 00:30:01.410
Now before time for this thing to expire.

00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:04.833
The East Pakistanis succeed from Pakistan

00:30:04.833 --> 00:30:07.830
and form of a new nation to Bangladesh.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:10.190
And the preferences continued right on

00:30:10.190 --> 00:30:12.860
because there were other
groups had been added to it

00:30:12.860 --> 00:30:14.990
and so once you get the constituency,

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:17.396
you can't say no to them.

00:30:17.396 --> 00:30:22.396
It is an argument that
has never worked out

00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:24.750
anywhere that I've been able to check.

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:25.583
- All right.

00:30:25.583 --> 00:30:28.340
So Tom Sowell says no
to the welfare state,

00:30:28.340 --> 00:30:30.385
no to affirmative action.

00:30:30.385 --> 00:30:32.440
What is to be done?

00:30:32.440 --> 00:30:34.880
And now you were kind
enough to share with me

00:30:35.830 --> 00:30:37.900
the galleys of your forthcoming edition of

00:30:37.900 --> 00:30:39.960
Discrimination and Disparities.

00:30:39.960 --> 00:30:42.340
Let me give you a few quotations from

00:30:42.340 --> 00:30:44.340
some of the new chapter in that book.

00:30:44.340 --> 00:30:49.287
Quote, "The poverty rate
among black married couples

00:30:49.287 --> 00:30:53.397
"has been less than 10%
every year since 1994.

00:30:53.397 --> 00:30:56.587
"As far back as 1969, young black males

00:30:56.587 --> 00:30:58.937
"whose homes included
newspapers, magazines,

00:30:58.937 --> 00:31:01.357
"and library cards had similar incomes

00:31:01.357 --> 00:31:03.687
"to those of their white counterparts.

00:31:03.687 --> 00:31:06.577
"Academic outcomes show
a pattern of disparities

00:31:06.577 --> 00:31:08.855
"similar to the pattern of disparities

00:31:08.855 --> 00:31:13.067
"in the amount of time
devoted to school work.

00:31:13.067 --> 00:31:18.067
"Apparently lifestyle
choices have consequences."

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:19.750
Close quote.

00:31:19.750 --> 00:31:22.454
So this is the constrained
vision once again.

00:31:22.454 --> 00:31:26.860
Welfare state that's government,
we don't rely on that.

00:31:26.860 --> 00:31:30.360
Affirmative action, government,
we don't rely on that.

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:32.437
We rely on hard work.

00:31:32.437 --> 00:31:35.782
We rely on the institution of marriage.

00:31:35.782 --> 00:31:38.260
That's correct?

00:31:38.260 --> 00:31:39.647
- Yes, in other words these things

00:31:39.647 --> 00:31:42.150
and I don't think it's
the marriage as such,

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:44.400
the library cards as such.

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:47.530
It's that there are lifestyle
choices that have been made

00:31:47.530 --> 00:31:49.870
and the comparison I made was between,

00:31:49.870 --> 00:31:52.522
if you look at the
poverty rate among blacks,

00:31:52.522 --> 00:31:56.461
it was a 22% and among whites was 11%,

00:31:56.461 --> 00:31:59.863
but among black married
couples it was 7.5%.

00:31:59.863 --> 00:32:03.160
So not only do better
than blacks as a whole,

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:05.110
they do better than whites as a whole,

00:32:05.110 --> 00:32:08.110
and so it's lifestyle choices.

00:32:08.110 --> 00:32:11.060
Similarly with the
results and some of these

00:32:11.060 --> 00:32:13.460
more successful charter schools

00:32:13.460 --> 00:32:16.550
that you have these kids not only meeting

00:32:16.550 --> 00:32:19.350
but exceeding the national standards

00:32:19.350 --> 00:32:23.530
in places like Harlem
and in the South Bronx.

00:32:23.530 --> 00:32:27.410
And these are not kids who
are skimming the cream.

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:29.479
They're kids chosen by lottery.

00:32:29.479 --> 00:32:32.020
They don't even test them for ability.

00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:34.180
They don't even look at
their academic records.

00:32:34.180 --> 00:32:35.690
They take it into the schools

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:37.700
and they and they have hard work

00:32:37.700 --> 00:32:39.660
and they make it clear at the outset

00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:42.390
and they don't tolerate a
lot of nonsensical behavior

00:32:42.390 --> 00:32:45.440
and these kids are doing incredibly.

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:47.000
- So Tom, here...

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.440
Again, I think back to the Moynihan,

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:53.140
well no I think the
Moynihan report in '65,

00:32:53.140 --> 00:32:57.820
and he was very alarmed
by the illegitimacy rate

00:32:57.820 --> 00:32:59.740
of 25% among African-Americans.

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:01.830
By the way in fairness
to the late Moynihan,

00:33:01.830 --> 00:33:04.240
we should point out, one
reason he was alarmed by this

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:06.620
was his own father had
walked out on the family

00:33:06.620 --> 00:33:07.620
when he was 10 years old.

00:33:07.620 --> 00:33:11.210
He experienced what it
meant to be two kids

00:33:11.210 --> 00:33:12.270
to have one parent.

00:33:12.270 --> 00:33:15.370
Okay and now it's all
gotten dramatically worse

00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:18.542
for whites and Hispanics
and blacks, for everybody.

00:33:18.542 --> 00:33:21.440
And then I think back beyond that

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:24.030
to your experience of Harlem.

00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:27.532
You drop out of high school and do what?

00:33:27.532 --> 00:33:29.490
Go on welfare?

00:33:29.490 --> 00:33:31.150
Start cashing, no.

00:33:31.150 --> 00:33:34.460
You went to work and you
spent some of that money

00:33:34.460 --> 00:33:37.253
to buy some inexpensive Encyclopedias.

00:33:38.610 --> 00:33:40.868
And Harlem was so...

00:33:40.868 --> 00:33:45.868
but I feel this counsel, it's
almost a counsel of despair

00:33:46.148 --> 00:33:50.270
in that world just seems
so utterly vanished.

00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:51.620
- No question.

00:33:51.620 --> 00:33:54.420
- So your argument is if we can stand up

00:33:54.420 --> 00:33:58.940
to the welfare state, we can
somehow get back to that world,

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:01.949
a family family structure
will reassert itself?

00:34:01.949 --> 00:34:06.330
- That that's gonna be
reconquering the same ground,

00:34:06.330 --> 00:34:09.854
which is very tough to
do but it can be done.

00:34:09.854 --> 00:34:14.854
I was so lucky at the time I
had no clue about all this.

00:34:15.085 --> 00:34:17.140
I left home in 1948,

00:34:19.026 --> 00:34:24.026
many decades later I learned
that the unemployment rate

00:34:25.280 --> 00:34:30.280
among black teenagers in 1948
16, 17 year olds was 9.4%.

00:34:33.684 --> 00:34:37.560
Among whites the same age it was 10.2%.

00:34:37.560 --> 00:34:41.680
So both blacks and white
teenagers had only a fraction

00:34:41.680 --> 00:34:44.490
of the unemployment that they have today.

00:34:44.490 --> 00:34:45.610
- You were expected to work,

00:34:45.610 --> 00:34:47.580
you were expected to be able to get a job.

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:50.193
- And more importantly the
jobs were there for you.

00:34:51.075 --> 00:34:55.119
And this is because of a fluke really.

00:34:55.119 --> 00:34:58.120
The minimum wage law in the United States,

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:00.290
Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938

00:35:01.450 --> 00:35:04.730
was passed with specified rates of pay

00:35:04.730 --> 00:35:06.730
that you're supposed to get.

00:35:06.730 --> 00:35:11.480
Almost immediately inflation
took off during the 1940s,

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:15.840
so by 1948 those numbers were
in the law were meaningless.

00:35:15.840 --> 00:35:16.900
- Oh I see.

00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:19.060
- In other words when I started out

00:35:19.060 --> 00:35:20.940
as a Western Union messenger,

00:35:20.940 --> 00:35:23.830
the minimum wage was 40 cents an hour.

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:27.100
I started out at the
bottom at 65 cents an hour.

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:29.790
So it was the same as if
there was no minimum wage

00:35:29.790 --> 00:35:31.757
and this is what happened, you had this,

00:35:31.757 --> 00:35:33.700
and I was so lucky, I of course,

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:35.690
had no clue about any of this.

00:35:35.690 --> 00:35:39.645
Now a black kid 20 years
later comes in there.

00:35:39.645 --> 00:35:42.750
People have become compassionate.

00:35:42.750 --> 00:35:44.750
They've raised the minimum wage.

00:35:44.750 --> 00:35:46.508
So he can't get a job.

00:35:46.508 --> 00:35:50.440
And I don't think it does
any community any good

00:35:50.440 --> 00:35:53.346
to have a whole lot of teenage males

00:35:53.346 --> 00:35:57.043
hanging around on the streets
with no job and nothing to do.

00:35:57.043 --> 00:35:59.090
- Right.

00:35:59.090 --> 00:35:59.930
Tom so...

00:36:00.925 --> 00:36:03.420
another thought here.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:08.180
You're describing a world,
Harlem the urban world, gone.

00:36:08.180 --> 00:36:10.760
But you made visits when you were young,

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:13.110
you knew the south as well, didn't you?

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:15.130
You went back to the
south when you were young

00:36:15.130 --> 00:36:16.410
from time to time?

00:36:16.410 --> 00:36:18.140
I said back to the south
because as I recall

00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:19.050
you were born in the south.

00:36:19.050 --> 00:36:21.530
- Yeah, I went to New York.

00:36:21.530 --> 00:36:25.010
Yeah, well I think this was
courtesy of the Marine Corps,

00:36:25.010 --> 00:36:28.700
which happened to locate the
boot camp in South Carolina

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:31.040
and had Camp Lejeune in North Carolina.

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:33.860
- So what I'm getting at is
you were of the generation

00:36:33.860 --> 00:36:36.357
that saw Jim Crow with your own eyes.

00:36:36.357 --> 00:36:38.070
- Oh, no question, no question.

00:36:38.070 --> 00:36:39.140
- Okay.

00:36:39.140 --> 00:36:42.500
So well here's, let me
read you a quotation.

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:45.800
This is from a article
that got a lot of attention

00:36:45.800 --> 00:36:48.000
in the Atlantic a couple years ago called

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.166
The Case For Reparations
by Ta-Nahesi Coates.

00:36:52.166 --> 00:36:55.867
Quote, "White supremacy
is a force so fundamental

00:36:55.867 --> 00:36:58.687
"to America that it is
difficult to imagine

00:36:58.687 --> 00:37:00.127
"the country without it.

00:37:00.127 --> 00:37:02.787
"Reparations is the price we must pay

00:37:02.787 --> 00:37:05.340
"to see ourselves squarely."

00:37:05.340 --> 00:37:06.720
Close quote.

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.900
And Tom Sowell who actually
saw Jim Crow with his own eyes

00:37:09.900 --> 00:37:11.970
and experienced it responds how?

00:37:11.970 --> 00:37:16.970
- It would be nice to know
his evidence of what he said,

00:37:17.334 --> 00:37:19.543
just to be old-fashioned about it.

00:37:21.825 --> 00:37:24.347
No, it was a rotten system,

00:37:24.347 --> 00:37:28.747
but I don't know how we get
from that to reparations.

00:37:28.747 --> 00:37:31.898
I mean what we see in the United States

00:37:31.898 --> 00:37:36.356
in terms of the bad things,
you see all around the world.

00:37:36.356 --> 00:37:39.060
If you were to give
reparations to everyone

00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:41.770
whose ancestors had been slaves,

00:37:41.770 --> 00:37:44.270
I suspect that you would
have to give reparations

00:37:44.270 --> 00:37:47.770
to more than a half the entire
population of the globe.

00:37:47.770 --> 00:37:51.810
Slavery was not confined
to one set of races.

00:37:51.810 --> 00:37:54.470
I suspect that most of the
people who either were slaves

00:37:54.470 --> 00:37:56.560
or slave owners around the world

00:37:56.560 --> 00:37:58.010
were neither white nor black.

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:01.480
I mean this was this was a universal curse

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:02.810
of the human species.

00:38:02.810 --> 00:38:04.800
- Africa, the Middle East, Asia,

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:06.367
slavery took place everywhere.

00:38:06.367 --> 00:38:11.367
- And continued elsewhere
long after it was abolished

00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:13.350
in the Western countries.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:18.350
- Let me try is sticking
with Ta-Nahesi Coates.

00:38:18.636 --> 00:38:22.670
Shelby Steele talks about white guilt.

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:25.100
And in Ta-Nahesi Coates you get

00:38:25.100 --> 00:38:27.030
almost the counterpart of that,

00:38:27.030 --> 00:38:31.870
a kind of African-American
claim against the white guilt

00:38:31.870 --> 00:38:33.500
and this seems...

00:38:35.210 --> 00:38:36.740
beginning with the abolitionist,

00:38:36.740 --> 00:38:39.500
even beginning before the Civil War,

00:38:39.500 --> 00:38:43.077
you seem every generation
there's some expression

00:38:43.077 --> 00:38:47.940
that racism and slavery
as Shelby calls it,

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:51.666
correctly of course, the
sin of slavery is so deeply

00:38:51.666 --> 00:38:52.810
and it's something we still live with,

00:38:52.810 --> 00:38:54.370
how do we expiate it?

00:38:54.370 --> 00:38:55.730
How do we get past it?

00:38:55.730 --> 00:38:57.810
Is there something we can do

00:38:57.810 --> 00:39:00.380
to relieve ourselves of this legacy?

00:39:00.380 --> 00:39:02.490
- Oh, I'd like you to repeat

00:39:02.490 --> 00:39:04.320
If you were a slave owner,

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:07.390
I don't see any reason why
you should feel differently.

00:39:07.390 --> 00:39:10.690
